^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|In NT, honor leads work as follows:

1) The lead of the King (the most common) asks partner to encourage with an honor, discourage with no honor. It is typically done from a long suit headed by King-Queen, so partner usually signals high with the Ace or Jack. Under no circumstances should partner encourage high-low with a doubleton. The lead specifically asks for attitude (e.g. does partner have an honor/) not count.|
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|2) The lead of an Ace asks partner to unblock an honor. It is typically done from AKJ10, so partner should pitch the Queen if he has it. But he should pitch any honor (K, Q, or J). If partner does not have an honor, then he gives count. The reason for giving count with no honor is that the opening leader can then figure out how many cards declarer has in the suit, and will know whether or not it makes sense to continue the suit or hope that his partner can get in and lead the suit through declarer.|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|3) The lead of the Queen most often is from a 3-card sequence of QJ10 or QJ9. However, on rare occasions, it is done from KQ109 and asks partner to pitch the Jack if he has it. This is so rare, I often don't bother to mention it, but it seems to be a favorite of bridge teachers and authors for some reason. So, the one time in your life when partner leads the Queen in NT and you happen to have the Jack and happen to remember this lesson, discard it.|
